<section xml:id="sect-practical-examples">
  <title>Practical Mathematical Examples</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      We start out with a few problems as examples that arise in mathematics where numerical analysis plays an important role.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-sqrt-65">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <em>Using only the four basic operations <m>+,-,\cdot, /</m> on a calculator, find <m>\sqrt{65}</m> to within 0.001.</em>
        </p>

        <p>
          Also, answer the following questions:
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write down the steps (the algorithm) that you used.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                How do you know your answer is correct to 3 decimal places?
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Can you use this technique to find <m>\sqrt{a}</m> to <m>d</m> decimal places for any positive number <m>a</m> and positive integer <m>d</m>? Explain.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      The following is a classic example of an example where numerical analysis helps another mathematical field, specifically Statistics.
      Typically users in an introductory class are given tables of distributions or use software to calculate probabilities.
      Where do those tables come from? How does the software perform the calculations?  The following specifically asks some questions related to the normal distribution.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-norm-distribution">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If a random variable, <m>X</m> is normally distributed with mean <m>\mu</m> and standard deviation <m>\sigma</m>, the probability density function can be written as
          <me>
            f(x;\mu,\sigma) = \frac{1}{\sigma \sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-(x-\mu)^2/\sigma^2}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          The probability that <m>X</m> is less than <m>a</m> is given by
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}P(X \lt a) \amp = \int_{-\infty}^{a} f(x;\mu,\sigma) \, dx \\
          \amp = \int_{-\infty}^{a} \frac{1}{\sigma \sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-(x-\mu)^2/\sigma^2}\, dx\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Here's a few standard questions:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              If we are given <m>\mu</m>, <m>\sigma</m> and <m>a</m>, how do we calculate <m>P(X&#x3C;a)</m>?
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              For a given <m>\mu</m> and <m>\sigma</m> and <m>k</m> for <m>0&#x3C;k&#x3C;1</m>, how do we solve <m>P(X&#x3C;a)=k</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    The following shows another common example in which data is given and information needs to be extracted from it.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="ex-hard-disk-prices">
